We need to do some data wrangling to convert data types into more appropriate types¶

1) Convert start_station_id, end_station_id and member_birth_year columns to int instead of float

2) Convert duration_sec to minutes instead of seconds to be more readable and rename column to duration_min

3) Convert start_time, end_time to datetime type

4) Convert user_type, member_gender to category type

5) Convert bike_share_for_all_trip to boolean type

6) Create day_of_week column using start_time to use in the data analysis

7) Create age column using member_birth_year & remove member_birth_year column

8) Create hour_of_day column using start_time to use in the data analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183,412 bike shares in the dataset with 16 features:

  • some variables are date times like ('start_time', 'end_time')

  • some are strings like ('start_station_name', 'end_station_name')

  • some are floats representing coordinates like ('start_station_latitude', 'start_station_longitude', 'end_station_latitude', 'end_station_longitude')

  • some are numeric represnting ids like ('start_station_id', 'end_station_id', 'bike_id')

  • one is numeric representing trip duration in seconds 'duration_sec'

  • one is numberic representing birth year of member 'member_birth_year'

  • some are strings representing categories ('user_type', 'member_gender')

  • one is string representing boolean value 'bike_share_for_all_trip'

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm interested in exploring dataset and answering some questions about the data & get some insights about how day of week, hour of day, trip duration and customer type affect other features.

Main Questions:¶

  • When are most trips taken in terms of time of day or day of the week?
  • How long does the average trip take?
  • Does the above depend on if a user is a subscriber or customer?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • Some features I'll use to get new features of interest like start_time which I'll use to get day of week and hour of the day and also member_birth_year which I'll use to get member age.

  • Some features I'll use to explore how features of interest interact with them like age, gender

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section we are interested to find answers for the following questions:¶

  • When are most trips taken in terms of time of day or day of the week?
  • How long does the average trip take?
  • What is the average age of users?

Also we want to take a look at distribution of the following columns:¶

  • Age
  • Gender
  • User Type
  • Day of week
  • Hour of day
  • Trip Duration

1. When are most trips taken in terms of time of day or day of the week?¶

Answer: Hour: 17, Day: Thursday

# let's put it on a log scale because there's a long tail 

log_binsize = 0.1

bins = 10 ** np.arange(0, np.log10(bike_shares_df['duration_min'].max()) + log_binsize, log_binsize)

plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.hist(data = bike_shares_df, x = 'duration_min', bins = bins)
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xticks([1, 5, 10, 50, 100, 500, 1000], [1, 5, 10, 50, 100, 500, '1k'])
plt.title('Trip duration distribution', fontsize=18)
plt.xlabel('Trip duration (min)', fontsize=16)
plt.ylabel('Frequency', fontsize=16)
plt.show()
Trip duration has a long-tailed distribution, with a lot of trips on the small trip duration end, and few on the large trip duration end. When plotted on a log-scale, the trip duration distribution looks normal distribution with mode around 11 min and has outliers above 1000 min with max of 1409 min.¶

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  • I exlopred some distributions of the features in the dataset including the Age, Gender, User Type, Day of week, Hour of day and Trip duration and I made transformation for Trip duration distribution to log scale.

  • Age distribution showed a right skewed distribution which has some outliers greaters than 100 which are a large numbers for the age but I think they are natural data and no need to be cleaned.

  • Gender distribution showed that males are the majority of the bike share users.

  • User type distribution showed that the the majority of bike share users are subscribers.

  • Day of week distribution showed that Saturday & Sunday are the lowest days in trips and this is reasonable as they are weekends and people don't get to work.

  • Hour of day distribution showed a bimodal distribution with two peaks in the 8 & 17 o'clock which are usually the starting & ending hours of the working day.

  • Trip duration has a long-tailed distribution and when plotted on a log-scale, it looks normal distribution with mean around 11 min and has outliers above 1000 min with max of 1409 min.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I did some cleaning to convert data types to more appropriate types and also generated some new columns like (age, day_of_week, hour_of_day) to use in my investigations.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

From the 4 relations we studies we obserbed that:

  • Other gender has the largest trip duration & women has more trip duration than men. Also on weekend days the trip duration decrease for all genders.

  • Other gender has the largest trip duration in hour 2 & 3 AM & men have significantly larger trip duration in early hours of the day than women while in the rest of the day they have converging trip durations.

  • Customers has larger trip durations than subscribers & they also make larger trips on weekends than work days.

  • Customers has the largest trip durations on hours 2 & 3 AM

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

From all relations we studied we can conclude some interesting insights:

  • Women have larger trip than men.

  • Customers have larger trips than subscribers & they ride for more time on holidays.

  • People in general ride more on working days & mostly on the start, end of day
